{"response":{"status":"ok","userTier":"internal","total":0,"startIndex":0,"pageSize":200,"currentPage":1,"pages":0,"orderBy":"newest","tag":{"id":"theguardian/mainsection","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"news","sectionName":"News","webTitle":"Main section","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection"},"results":[],"leadContent":[{"id":"education/2014/dec/02/faith-schools-not-tackle-problem-separate-lives","type":"article","sectionId":"education","sectionName":"Education","webPublicationDate":"2014-12-02T07:09:08Z","webTitle":"Dear Ms Morgan: how do faith schools tackle the problem of ‘separate lives’? | Michael Rosen","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/dec/02/faith-schools-not-tackle-problem-separate-lives","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/education/2014/dec/02/faith-schools-not-tackle-problem-separate-lives","fields":{"headline":"Dear Ms Morgan: how do faith schools tackle the problem of ‘separate lives’?","standfirst":"The PM is worried about different cultures living apart from each other, but more free schools of specific faiths isn’t going to help","trailText":"The PM is worried about different cultures living apart from each other, but more free schools of specific faiths isn’t going to help","byline":"Michael Rosen","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e45b98e75effaa0c934931b24bc4281d1207c243\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/28/1417177828331/Faith-schools-011.jpg\" alt=\"Faith schools\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">'I could set up an \"ethnically Jewish\" school … And what would I have achieved? I would have pulled some children out of schools where they had mixed with children of many faiths.' Photograph: Graham Turner for the Guardian</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p>Dear Nicky Morgan</p> <p>In 2011, the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pms-speech-at-munich-security-conference\" title=\"\">prime minister said</a>: “Under the doctrine of state multiculturalism, we have encouraged different cultures to live separate lives, apart from each other and apart from the mainstream. We’ve failed to provide a vision of society to which they feel they want to belong.”</p> <p>Though David Cameron used the word “state” in front of “multiculturalism”, his speech was widely reported as telling us that it was the bit about living our “different cultures” that had been a disaster. <a href=\"http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-12371994\" title=\"\">Laura Kuenssberg on the BBC website wrote</a>: “In frank language he made abundantly clear he believes multiculturalism has failed.”</p> <p>At the time, I didn’t hear anyone in government rushing to correct any ambiguity around what the prime minister actually said. The “vision” that teachers should “provide” has turned out to be the “<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jun/09/michael-gove-british-values-curriculum\" title=\"\">basic British values of democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty, mutual respect and tolerance for those of different faiths and beliefs</a>”.</p> <p>I guess we’re supposed to lay to one side the fact that these owe plenty to universalist ideas originating in France, the US and the United Nations rather than to something specifically British. The message I get here is that in education, we don’t need to bother about being historically accurate. Or is talking about “values” in a universal way in itself dangerously multicultural?</p> <p>Cameron’s speech came early on in this government. Subsequently, we’ve been offered free schools. People like me have opposed these on the grounds that they get in the way of providing the same educational opportunities to all children and can lead to the absurd situation I heard played out on Radio 4’s Today programme in which a local authority is accused of not intervening in so-called problem schools over which it has no control – as has happened in Tower Hamlets recently. How handy for you that it wasn’t you being grilled by the interviewer. And yet, in your government’s rush to create schools controlled by your office, it’s your office that encourages “state multiculturalism”, which according to Cameron leads to us having “separate lives”, and can result in “Islamist extremism” and “terrorism”.</p> <p>I nipped over to the “<a href=\"http://www.newschoolsnetwork.org/what-are-free-schools/find-a-free-school\" title=\"\">Find a free school near you</a>” page at the New Schools Network site and found more than 30 schools which appear to provide a culturally specific faith ethos, whether that’s dubbed Islamic, Muslim, Jewish, Sikh, Hindu, Christian, Church of England or Catholic.</p> <p>I fully concede that this is a guess – and people will correct me if I’m wrong – but I doubt if there are many Muslims in the Jewish schools on this list, nor let’s say, many Catholics in the Hindu schools, or Jews in the Hindu schools … and so on. Doesn’t that encourage people to lead “separate lives”? When people set up free schools with a faith name on the board outside, don’t they tend to give off a signal about who’s welcome to come inside? Why else set them up?</p> <p>I gather that these days, I’m what’s known as “ethnically Jewish”. I could set up an “ethnically Jewish” school, couldn’t I? I could agree to abide by all the conditions on your website; on the board outside my school I could write “The Michael Rosen Ethnically Jewish School”. If I set this up in north London, say, I can imagine that it might attract a few parents.</p> <p>And what would I have achieved? I would have pulled some children out of schools where they had mixed with children of many faiths, no faith, many cultures and mixed cultures. Ofsted would of course pop in to make sure I was teaching “British values” so I would take care to not call them “universal”. Likewise, <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/11253436/Ofsted-rural-schools-failing-to-promote-British-values.html\" title=\"\">as Ofsted have instructed some rural schools recently</a>, I’d have to teach “diversity” even as we were practising the opposite.</p> <p>As I thought some more about my ethnically Jewish school, I wondered what kind of encouragement would the state give me, even though Cameron has warned me of the dangers of this? This time I nipped over to the government’s own website to see what kind of <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/326402/201407v3_Single_FA_mainstream_published.pdf\" title=\"\">financial assistance</a> I might expect from your office.</p> <p>Here I learned that: “The secretary of state will pay grants towards recurrent expenditure and may pay grants towards capital expenditure” for my free school. Recurrent expenditure “means any money spent on the establishment, conduct, administration and maintenance” of my school, apart from the  capital expenditure which means expenditure on such things as: “acquiring land and buildings”; and “such other items … of a substantial or enduring nature which the secretary of state agrees are capital expenditure...” This may also include “funding for any other costs to the academy [or free school] which the secretary of state considers necessary”.</p> <p>That’s quite a lot of “encouragement”. Cameron should be told.</p> <p><strong>Yours, Michael Rosen</strong></p>","newspaperPageNumber":"42","wordcount":"822","commentCloseDate":"2014-12-05T07:09:08Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2014-11-28T12:17:11Z","firstPublicationDate":"2014-12-02T07:09:08Z","internalComposerCode":"547867c7e4b0c45a9ee684fe","internalOctopusCode":"9818557","internalPageCode":"2200709","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-07-19T14:19:24Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-12-02T00:00:00Z","publication":"The Guardian"