12.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"669122a631ce5278f0973914ce8a608c87351766","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"200522794-001","copyright":"Getty Images","picdarUrn":"GD*3863547"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/21/1416571860954/education-research-007.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"education research","caption":"'The knowledge and skills that children are taught are not a matter just for politicians … we all have a stake in it.' Photograph: Ableimages/Getty Images","credit":"Photograph: Ableimages/Getty Images","photographer":"Ableimages","source":"Getty Images","width":"220","height":"132","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/21/1416571860954/education-research-007.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"669122a631ce5278f0973914ce8a608c87351766","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"200522794-001","copyright":"Getty Images","picdarUrn":"GD*3863547"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/21/1416571863139/education-research-009.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"education research","caption":"'The knowledge and skills that children are taught are not a matter just for politicians … we all have a stake in it.' Photograph: Ableimages/Getty Images","credit":"Photograph: Ableimages/Getty Images","photographer":"Ableimages","source":"Getty Images","width":"300","height":"180","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/21/1416571863139/education-research-009.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"669122a631ce5278f0973914ce8a608c87351766","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"200522794-001","copyright":"Getty Images","picdarUrn":"GD*3863547"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/21/1416571864216/education-research-010.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"education research","caption":"'The knowledge and skills that children are taught are not a matter just for politicians … we all have a stake in it.' Photograph: Ableimages/Getty Images","credit":"Photograph: Ableimages/Getty Images","photographer":"Ableimages","source":"Getty Images","width":"380","height":"228","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/21/1416571864216/education-research-010.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"669122a631ce5278f0973914ce8a608c87351766","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"200522794-001","copyright":"Getty Images","picdarUrn":"GD*3863547"}}]}],"isHosted":false},{"id":"education/2014/nov/18/half-baked-a-level-reform-rushed-election","type":"article","sectionId":"education","sectionName":"Education","webPublicationDate":"2014-11-18T07:10:03Z","webTitle":"This half-baked A-level reform is being rushed for the election | Laura McInerney","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/nov/18/half-baked-a-level-reform-rushed-election","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/education/2014/nov/18/half-baked-a-level-reform-rushed-election","fields":{"headline":"This half-baked A-level reform is being rushed for the election","standfirst":"Schools, students, exam boards and universities aren’t ready but the change to ‘one-shot’ exams is happening anyway","trailText":"Schools, students, exam boards and universities aren’t ready but the change to ‘one-shot’ exams is happening anyway, says <strong>Laura McInerney</strong>","byline":"Laura McInerney","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"fd9a27608f874d6053dbac6d3a3e10ee8a84965d\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/11/13/1415900067119/A-levels-011.jpg\" alt=\"A-levels\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">From next September A-levels will return to being a two-year qualification with exams taken at the end of the period. Photograph: David Davies/PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p>There’s a debacle going on in our schools that no one is talking about – especially not the government. That is wrong, because it will potentially mess up the lives of children turning 16 this academic year. So let’s talk about it.</p> <p>For the past 14 years, if you sat A-levels, your final grade was based on a number of exams taken at different points across your two years of study. If you did badly at one, you could resit. Beyond giving more opportunities for improving grades, this process had two other advantages. First, universities could see the grades so far achieved by a student when they applied for a place. And second, students could drop subjects at the halfway point while still receiving a formal (AS) qualification.</p> <p>From next September, however, the government has decreed that A-levels will return to being a two-year qualification. Exams will all be taken, just once, at the end of the two years’ study. The mid-point AS exams will be stripped out and offered as a standalone qualification.</p> <p>At first, this doesn’t sound too much of a debacle. Won’t sixth forms just offer the standalone AS levels first and then have students sit the full A-level in their second year? Well, no. Because, in its wisdom, the government asked exam boards to make sure the materials don’t easily overlap. Ministers want students to either do the AS or the A-level, but not both.</p> <p>So which do you take? No one knows. Cue debacle. Government sentiment is that the new A-levels are more “rigorous” and universities prefer them. Though given that almost all degree courses are modular, I expect “universities” is more likely to be ministerial shorthand for “my mates who are professors at a couple of Oxbridge colleges”.</p> <p>There were suggestions when the changes were announced that they would reduce the amount of teaching time that was being lost to exams and that they would relieve stress on students. This sudden concern for students’ stress levels seems disingenuous from a party intent on assessing four-year-olds and which had to be talked down from ranking children in their primary school exams. ​​</p> <p>B​esides, it’s not true. Without formal AS ​exams at the end of year 12, sixth forms will ​likely still run mock exams to ensure students are well-practised and can check their progress. As for stress, the one-shot nature of A-level exams​ will likely send student blood pressure skywards.</p> <p>Then there are the practical problems facing schools and colleges with the policy’s implementation. Funding to sixth forms has been cut; they will now receive funds only for three subjects per student. Given the lack of overlap between AS and A-level, it’s likely that only the brightest students would cope with sitting both. Solely offering three A-levels, and ditching AS levels ​entirely, seems the best option to many.</p> <p>This,​ though, comes at a price. Faced with “one shot” exams, students pick safer choices. “Try it for AS, and drop it if it’s too hard” is a common coaxing option in subjects such as maths and foreign languages, in which teenagers often have low confidence despite good skill levels.</p> <p>Cambridge University last week added a further twist when it <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-29914310\" title=\"\">wrote to schools</a> urging them not just to do A-levels but to enter students for the standalone AS. Its reasoning is sound: without AS grades students will be selected for university places based on less-recent GCSEs, or the notoriously unreliable <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/oct/22/half-a-level-grade-predictions-wrong\" title=\"\">predicted grades</a>.</p> <p>Even if schools and colleges can pick their way through the minefield and find a sensible way to deal with this for their students, it’s still likely that the summer of 2017 will culminate in problems. Students will sit all of their new exams at once; exam boards will have to mark them – all at once – and no one has the foggiest how grades will be affected by the newly introduced “rigour”. If it works as it should, grades ought to go down. What does this mean for university offers? No one knows, but a good guess is that students just returning from a gap year, with A-levels already under their belts, will be at a serious advantage over thousands of others now unexpectedly getting lower grades – who will be plunged into the chaotic clearing system to find a university place.</p> <p>The education secretary said in a speech this year that she didn’t believe the government had acted too fast. She wants to <a href=\"http://press.conservatives.com/post/98807929855/nicky-morgan-speech-to-conservative-party-conference\" title=\"\">plough on</a> with this “reform”.</p> <p>But with something this half-cooked it has to be worth delaying – even if just for a year. Exam boards still haven’t released their syllabuses, universities don’t know what they want, funding is tumultuous. The only reason for barrelling ahead is because there’s an election next year. But that is irrelevant if you’re a teenager making decisions about your entire future.</p> <p>We need to talk about this issue, and the government needs to fix it now. Sixteen-year-olds will only live this year once. Let’s not disrupt their futures for the sake of an election.</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"43","wordcount":"851","commentCloseDate":"2014-11-21T07:10:03Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2014-11-13T17:23:03Z","firstPublicationDate":"2014-11-18T07:10:03Z","internalComposerCode":"5464e8f7e4b0cb80d027b802","internalOctopusCode":"9758771","internalPageCode":"2192448","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-07-19T14:22:35Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-11-18T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/43acy","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","lang":"en","internalRevision":"