type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146104750/David-Cameron-007.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"David Cameron","caption":"David Cameron's speech outlined plans to extend the role of regional commissioners giving them authority over all schools. Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","credit":"Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","photographer":"Neil Hall","source":"Reuters","width":"220","height":"132","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146104750/David-Cameron-007.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-fc-01cd5dca-c425-42db-94ec-10a20a8eb362","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"NGH08","copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*47543325"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146105810/David-Cameron-008.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"David Cameron","caption":"David Cameron's speech outlined plans to extend the role of regional commissioners giving them authority over all schools. Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","credit":"Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","photographer":"Neil Hall","source":"Reuters","width":"280","height":"168","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146105810/David-Cameron-008.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-fc-01cd5dca-c425-42db-94ec-10a20a8eb362","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"NGH08","copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*47543325"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146106883/David-Cameron-009.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"David Cameron","caption":"David Cameron's speech outlined plans to extend the role of regional commissioners giving them authority over all schools. Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","credit":"Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","photographer":"Neil Hall","source":"Reuters","width":"300","height":"180","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146106883/David-Cameron-009.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-fc-01cd5dca-c425-42db-94ec-10a20a8eb362","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"NGH08","copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*47543325"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146107985/David-Cameron-010.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"David Cameron","caption":"David Cameron's speech outlined plans to extend the role of regional commissioners giving them authority over all schools. Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","credit":"Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","photographer":"Neil Hall","source":"Reuters","width":"380","height":"228","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146107985/David-Cameron-010.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-fc-01cd5dca-c425-42db-94ec-10a20a8eb362","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"NGH08","copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*47543325"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146111911/David-Cameron-013.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"David Cameron","caption":"David Cameron's speech outlined plans to extend the role of regional commissioners giving them authority over all schools. Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","credit":"Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","photographer":"Neil Hall","source":"Reuters","width":"1860","height":"1116","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146111911/David-Cameron-013.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-fc-01cd5dca-c425-42db-94ec-10a20a8eb362","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"NGH08","copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*47543325"}},{"type":"image","file":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146114476/David-Cameron-014.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"David Cameron","caption":"David Cameron's speech outlined plans to extend the role of regional commissioners giving them authority over all schools. Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","credit":"Photograph: Neil Hall/Reuters","photographer":"Neil Hall","source":"Reuters","width":"2560","height":"1536","secureFile":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414146114476/David-Cameron-014.jpg","displayCredit":"false","mediaId":"gu-fc-01cd5dca-c425-42db-94ec-10a20a8eb362","imageType":"Photograph","suppliersReference":"NGH08","copyright":"REUTERS","picdarUrn":"GD*47543325"}}]}],"isHosted":false},{"id":"education/2014/oct/28/-sp-verdict-ofsted-requires-improvement","type":"article","sectionId":"education","sectionName":"Education","webPublicationDate":"2014-10-28T07:30:05Z","webTitle":"The verdict on Ofsted: ‘requires improvement’?","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/oct/28/-sp-verdict-ofsted-requires-improvement","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/education/2014/oct/28/-sp-verdict-ofsted-requires-improvement","fields":{"headline":"The verdict on Ofsted: ‘requires improvement’?","standfirst":"The schools watchdog is holding a consultation on its future. At Education Guardian, we held our own public inquiry…","trailText":"The schools watchdog is holding a consultation on its future. At Education Guardian, we held our own public inquiry…","byline":"Rebecca Ratcliffe","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-4020f727-137a-4f3a-9994-48f0dcba32e3\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/24/1414150355083/Michael-Wilshaw-head-of-O-011.jpg\" alt=\"Michael Wilshaw, head of Ofsted\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Sir Michael Wilshaw, chief inspector of schools, was recently the subject of a leaked DfE memo showing politicians’ concerns over Ofsted. Photograph: Felix Clay</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p>Ofsted has been dogged by criticism lately: accusations of political bias, complaints by headteachers that its judgments seem arbitrary, politicians privately commenting that the agency is poorly managed, or unions warning that the system is causing unnecessary stress. There have been allegations that some headteachers have found out the date of inspections in advance. The watchdog has undertaken a new consultation on a draft “framework” – its inspection guidelines – including shorter, more frequent inspections and a toughening up of safeguarding issues, following some highly damaging failures. It also recently published a “myth-busting” guide to clarify its position on lesson-grading and the amount of marking expected. Will all this silence Ofsted’s critics?</p> <h2>Kenny Frederick, retired headteacher of a secondary school in Tower Hamlets<br /></h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"484326446ea9e4fd2bd54a370001a634517b22ed\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414150613603/42b93f12-9aaf-4f9d-9bc4-a292d97b01d4-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Kenny Frederick\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Kenny Frederick </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Baron for the Guardian</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>I think Ofsted has had its day. Things have improved over time and schools have never been so good. I visit many across the country as a consultant and I’m blown away with the work schools are doing – yet the rhetoric from her majesty’s chief inspector is always negative. With what end? Teachers have had enough and very few want to be heads.</p> <p>Teachers are under intolerable pressure as heads, local authorities and academy sponsors panic about the next Ofsted and the next set of results. I feel very sorry for the many heads of schools in deprived areas whose results have fallen dramatically this year because of all the changes to exams. They fear this will trigger a no-notice inspection, and so it goes on. Teachers are no longer free to take risks in the classroom or be creative. Opportunities to take children out and see things are severely curtailed due to the need to move results up.</p> <p>Heads and teachers are frightened to speak out in case Ofsted are watching and might come in unexpectedly. My own staff often used to question my outspoken stance on the subject in case we all suffered as a result. But I think more heads need to stand up and be counted.</p> <h2>Jonathan Simons, head of education, Policy Exchange thinktank and founder of Greenwich free school, London </h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"7f85b6732ab76914cad71dae727358d45b7d9c88\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414151077254/a2c5f141-b57c-41b2-9365-cf3c34213e4f-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Jonathan Simons.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Jonathan Simons. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Ofsted should be a hygiene inspector, not a food critic. By that I mean it should be headteachers who are the dominant actors: they should be the ones saying this is what we’re doing, these are the outcomes, here’s the data to prove it. Ofsted should be validating and challenging that judgment rather than making the judgment themselves.</p> <p>The move to end graded lesson observations is a good one, but I’d take it further. Whenever you have Ofsted inspectors sitting at the back of a lesson they are inevitably going to be judging that lesson in order to judge the quality of teaching overall. Ofsted’s scrutiny should be of the head and governors and the decisions they’re making, rather than just making their own drop-in judgments.</p> <h2>Vicky Peel, parent of three, Peckham</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"69837ee4540c8db25956b7775ae36e3ea8f06bff\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414151192627/2bf5777d-2557-44c8-aa9f-6b19df4441aa-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Vicky Peel\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Vicky Peel</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>When Ofsted came into my son’s school, I feel they had a very particular set of ideas about the place and found stuff accordingly. The school was placed in special measures, which was a very destructive process for everybody – including the children, who were furious that their school had been trashed. It wasn’t reflective of their experience as students, or mine as a parent.</p> <p>I would like Ofsted to come in and, if schools do need support, then I’d like them to offer some, but I don’t feel that happens. Instead, it’s like a damning judgment most of the time. The stress it puts teachers through is palpable.</p> <h2>Richard Pring, retired director of the department of educational studies at Oxford University</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"28b395578830feef6e6a7cd138772e7f3dbf4a74\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414151297398/a65697fc-ec1a-4df3-b32c-c5781d5e5baf-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Richard Pring.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Richard Pring.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Anna Gordon</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In the last few decades there has been a transformation of her majesty’s inspectors as a totally independent body to what is now Ofsted. This occurred 20 or so years ago, when the head of Ofsted became a political appointment. There needs to be a return to that independent tradition, where inspectors were appointed from within HMI and received two years of intensive training.</p> <h2>Francis Gilbert, English and media studies teacher in outer London<br /></h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"e88475b5fc5e2d614df166c20307de326a7248c5\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414151393417/90573670-6449-442e-8206-9d530147f612-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg\" alt=\"Francis Gilbert.\" width=\"84\" height=\"126\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Francis Gilbert.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>When I first started teaching, Ofsted would come in and spend two weeks in a school looking quite closely at what we were doing and they would then write up a measured judgment. Nowadays, it seems like they’ve made the decision before they arrive based on exam data which actually isn’t reliable because you can just drill students on passing tests. It’s a garbage-in, garbage-out system. Ofsted needs to be looking at whether students are being challenged to think – and not drilled as robots to pass tests, which is happening in some schools. Ofsted may talk the talk but the reality is they actually encourage this kind of behaviour because they are too enthralled with their political masters who are in love with exam results.</p> <h2>Russell Hobby, general secretary of National Association of Headteachers</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"14eac560971c5392703b256e9d4e68c8cf385e66\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414151464692/db570e93-2fbb-4037-b45b-8068bde8841a-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Russell Hobby.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Russell Hobby.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Martin Godwin</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Michael Wilshaw’s sincerity is glaringly obvious for everybody, but the very authoritarian strategy he used when he was a head doesn’t work when applied across a whole system. It creates an awful lot of anxiety and hostility, which eventually is going to undermine what he is trying to achieve. For schools, Ofsted feels like a trial where you’re defending yourself against an aggressive prosecution. You don’t learn from the experience.</p> <p>We think the first layer of inspection should be a peer review process, where schools come in and inspect each other. Ofsted should be moderating and quality assuring that peer review process and intervening where there’s a risk of failure. Ofsted, which is an industrial-scale enterprise, would be better if it did less and focused on areas of risk where it did high-quality inspections.</p> <h2>Jackie Schneider, primary school music teacher in south London</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"be7c6a3d2660dc6ae0034bfcc371cb529fe7aae4\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414151554507/0dd30ffa-b782-4661-9cb9-f3128999a4a9-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Jackie Schneider.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Jackie Schneider.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Amit Lennon</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Ofsted has completely mangled the English language: we had the word “satisfactory” which meant it was OK. Now, if you say it in a school, it means terrible. If you tell a teacher that they’re good, then they well up because what they hear is: it’s OK, but it’s not outstanding.</p> <p>The overwhelming feeling of most teachers is joy and relief at surviving and getting shot of Ofsted – people don’t walk around inspired afterwards. It’s not a driver for improvement. Ofsted has been really good at getting schools to be good at Ofsted, which is completely self-serving. There’s an entire industry of consultants selling advice on how to get in the outstanding category – I’d like to know how much schools are frittering away on this.</p> <h2>Beatrice Merrick, chief executive of the British Association for Early Childhood Education</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"9146513acf9bb1aadd55c4aaa886ccc4813baad5\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159190453/ff0e9ca4-9f12-4d79-a6b7-592dd5ce9f84-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Beatrice Merrick\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Beatrice Merrick</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The new framework’s proposal not to inspect new early years settings for up to 30 months is a huge concern. The idea of two and a half years of children going through a setting that has had no inspection is really worrying. We are already anxious that there is a big backlog with early years inspections more generally: some haven’t been inspected for five or six years when they’re supposed to be inspected every four years.</p> <p>Of the inspections that have taken place, there have been a very high level of complaints about the quality of inspectors – in many cases this is thought to be caused by outsourcing. It is disappointing that while Ofsted is taking the rest of inspections back in-house, it’s not doing so for early years. This is for reasons we can understand – linked to the length of contracts and so on – but there’s a real concern that the quality of inspections is not good enough.</p> <h2>Dave Penman, general secretary of the FDA, the union representing senior personnel in Ofsted</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"df8078595b424293874ac992dc1c4d78d25ae1a6\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159256016/a6955125-32be-47ef-8f08-9e5df6f3e010-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Dave Penman\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Dave Penman.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Steve Maisey/Photoshot</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Ofsted is supposed to be independent of government yet, clearly, various voices and forces within government, will brief against what they’re doing or the people involved in it. That undermines the independence of the inspection regime – something which inspectors take very seriously – and damages its credibility among parents and teachers. School inspections have always been a political hot potato, with a lot of very strong ideological positions taken on all sides – but that creates a perfect storm around inspections. In the middle of it, all of the good work that inspectors do is lost.</p> <h2>Dr Michael Firth, headteacher of the Meridian school in Royston, Cambridgeshire, which won an appeal against Ofsted </h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"29a811e9712c6811dbe29d4b12481f5a2cebf2dc\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159331490/0b394cf4-b8b5-4dd5-8928-2e8f12a9ad25-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Michael Firth.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Michael Firth.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: stephen bond</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Pretty much every term the framework is republished in some form, which makes it difficult for schools – and inspection teams – to keep up. Certainly the last inspection we had, the inspection team didn’t follow the framework and we weren’t given an accurate outcome [the inspection team said the school required improvement but the school appealed and won]. The inspection was part of the old system using private contractors, which thankfully is changing now that all inspections from next September will go in-house.</p> <p>At the moment, my school is awaiting inspection and the state of alert is a distraction. But the process suggested in the new framework is proportionate – you would have one day with two in-house inspectors, rather than a two-day inspection with a team of four people. The sad thing is that this change will only apply to schools that are good or outstanding.</p> <h2>Tim Brighouse, former chief commissioner for London schools</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"32a58c66cc4c6624934c1c6dc6d9c9cf63a9ac73\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159402039/074d460e-eb7b-44bd-952d-317bfe5da8fa-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Tim Brighouse.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tim Brighouse.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Sam Frost</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Unlike some, I don’t believe Ofsted can be blamed for things going wrong in Birminghamschools – it isn’t the job of an inspector to spot extremism. The blame lies squarely with the secretary of state and the local authority. Ofsted was sucked into a task for which it was ill equipped.</p> <p>The body seems to have become confused as to what its role is and it appears too closely involved in policy to be credible.</p> <p>My view is that we need a regional school improvement system: I would have it democratically accountable to a board made up of representatives of local authorities in the area and professionals. If a region had cause to doubt a school or had concerns, you could then use a national Ofsted that otherwise would be keeping an eye on national standards and trends, and advising the secretary of state on policy.</p> <p>At the moment people are too micromanaged. Though it is to Wilshaw’s credit that politicians find him too independent, the recently leaked <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/oct/09/gove-ofsted-inspector-wilshaw-memo\" title=\"\">DfE memo</a> shows the appalling view of politicians that they have to control inspectors.</p> <h2>Tim Browse, headteacher of Hillcrest primary school in Bristol</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"36637581debf2d3f24230cf8c5191b439f3940df\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159458930/fd103e48-064b-49e8-a7c4-2406a743389b-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Tim Browse\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Tim Browse</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Broadly speaking, I quite like the proposals for a new framework, but I don’t like the slightly tokenistic way that it includes the need to prepare children for life in modern Britain. It has so much potential to go wrong. It’s so vague: are we going to be given a list of what British values are? I worry that it’s going to be a case of cutting and pasting a few things on to your website and that’s that box ticked. The fundamental reasons of why they’re pushing this issue are actually really serious, and need a more careful consideration.</p> <h2>Debra Kidd, advanced skills teacher, Saddleworth secondary school in Oldham</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"35be0c248998a31e51629e16b69a664307132351\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159523939/9396ff7d-63b3-4ae5-9bd9-a0cf71a358fd-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Debra Kidd\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Debra Kidd</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Twiddling with the frameworks will never work unless you take away the fear factor. People worry so much about Ofsted that the whole school system has become geared towards what they think inspectors might want.</p> <p>Whenever there seems to be a move in the right direction, for example stopping grading lessons, the emphasis moves to something else. Because there was a suggestion by Ofsted that progress would be measured by looking at books – schools suddenly switched their marking policies around. So now you’re getting primary school teachers who are expected to mark 90 books every night of the week, and secondary school teachers with 200-400 students who are now expected to mark those books in a week. The job of a teacher has become unsustainable unless you’re willing to put 70- or 80-hour weeks in.</p> <p>Headteachers have become like Premier League football managers and so they fear a poor set of results because it might lead to a poor report. Heads put downward pressure on staff, and staff put pressure on the children. The school is just working under a buckling system of stress as a result.</p> <h2>Geoff Barton, headteacher, King Edward VI School, Bury St Edmunds</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"b9fb58231479b34542570342176998c59bf7e35c\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159800861/127df9ce-ced5-4612-bdc5-9f3d64ae7f18-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg\" alt=\"Geoff Barton\" width=\"90\" height=\"135\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Geoff Barton</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>When inspecting teaching, one of the things that Ofsted has unhelpfully done is warp people’s views of what good practice is. If you talk about progress, people see it as a 20-minute slice of a lesson in which a teacher very artificially gets children to demonstrate that they know more at the end of the 20 minutes than they did at the beginning. Ofsted has become too formulaic.</p> <p>The reports feel as if they could have been phoned in from a desk somewhere else. The distinctiveness of a school isn’t noticed and things that count to parents – whether there is a school orchestra, a debating society, whether the uniform is smart – increasingly aren’t mentioned.</p> <h2>‘Disappointed Idealist’, a secondary school teacher and blogger</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"040218fa99f6e26a9b032bd32c4caf1b6844ea5d\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159870462/a9175786-540d-4b28-b736-252fe99a7caf-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg\" alt=\"'Disappointed Idealist'\" width=\"126\" height=\"189\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">‘Disappointed Idealist’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Politicians have suddenly – in the run-up to an election – realised that the current teacher workload situation is unsustainable. But attempts to identify tasks to cut are doomed unless politicians recognise that a huge amount of unnecessary work originates with headteachers who feel under impossible pressures to deliver “WOW” (What Ofsted Wants). Until last year, the issue was that schools came to understand from inspections that lessons had to be delivered in a certain way. This drove teachers mad until Ofsted had to publicly issue guidance to its own inspectors. No sooner had that issue gone than the rumour went round that inspectors were demanding to see “dialogue with students” in marking. Suddenly, schools all over the country were demanding that teachers engage in what’s become known as “double-marking”, where the teacher marks the work, the student comments on the marking, the teacher then marks the student’s comment on the original marking and so on. It shows how fear of Ofsted is behind so much unnecessary work. The single biggest thing politicians could do would be to tell Ofsted to stop looking for specific inputs and instead focus on outcomes – letting teachers choose how best to teach while retaining accountability for results.</p> <h2>Sarah Chitson, a sixth form student in Oxfordshire</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"b869f65c58e8cac674c7e7ab20fbbe45c9ca83c5\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414159945152/81c41757-84b0-4a32-bfeb-42275ee1dcd3-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Sarah Chitson\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Sarah Chitson</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>I don’t think that Ofsted can tell what’s happening at the school if they are only there for a couple of days. I’ve seen teachers attempt to cram all of their different techniques into one lesson – the mini whiteboards, games and group activities/presentations – just because it’s the only lesson of theirs that Ofsted are going to see. They’re attempting to make one lesson representative of a few years’ worth of teaching, and I think that’s unfair on the teachers.</p> <h2>Andy Cole, principal of the College of North West London</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"062926dc507b7df31e10a7e883098bdc85c7835d\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414160001711/d9223f46-e59e-42d4-be23-3e6e83cfa144-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Andy Cole\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Andy Cole</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>From a college point of view, the new framework is adopting some of the bad practices of old regimes and becoming very school-centric. Within the suggested framework they’re talking about getting rid of individual subject reports. In a large FE college, we do a diverse range of specialist training – from construction to training for the visually impaired in computing. At the moment we get a report on one department, it might be engineering, for example, talking about this subject in real depth, which is very useful for us. If you’re doing away with that, then we’d just be left with a broad statement about the college, and no accurate reflection of our provision.</p> <h2>Sue Cowley, teacher trainer and writer</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"c19472cc61f076d0803dbc098caa20c289d5e4ee\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/10/24/1414160075639/f2c0cc0f-18af-49a4-a275-118660fafea6-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Sue Cowley.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Sue Cowley.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: christopher jones</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>I’m not sure the proposed reforms will work – the relationship between schools and Ofsted has become so muddied by what’s gone on in recent years. Ofsted have moved outside their remit and started talking about methods. And, because Wilshaw is so outspoken, we’ve got ourselves into a situation where he’ll say: “Ofsted want to see this,” and then everybody starts doing it. It’s not true that schools just do things to please Ofsted, but they are becoming like puppets. Really, we should have a situation where the Department for Education says what works best for children and then Ofsted come in and regulate things like safeguarding. They’re tinkering with the framework but I’m not sure that they’re going to be able to turn it into something that will work – I think they might have to start over again. </p>","newspaperPageNumber":"40","wordcount":"2769","commentCloseDate":"2014-10-31T07:30:05Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2014-10-24T11:20:34Z","firstPublicationDate":"2014-10-28T07:30:05Z","internalComposerCode":"544a36