 school; costs of forced academisation; and the smallest free schools","trailText":"Funding decisions announced on Tuesday; school websites adopt ‘British values’; more delays to Durand boarding school; costs of forced academisation; and the smallest free schools","byline":"Warwick Mansell","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-0e21ef33-d1f0-48b6-ba9d-cb44cd6cd59a\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/cartoons/2014/10/10/1412957943864/Teacher-training-011.jpg\" alt=\"Teacher training\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The DfE will announce its funding allocations for teacher training on Tuesday 14 October. Photograph: Tomasz Trojanowski /Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<h2>School-based courses expected to be big winner in teacher training funding decision<br /></h2> <p>The future of thriving PGCE courses at some of England’s leading universities could be threatened on Tuesday as the Department for Education issues funding allocations for 2015-16. Some courses rated outstanding by Ofsted – possibly including Cambridge University’s – are facing drastic cutbacks as ministers press ahead with controversial plans to hand control over training to schools. The move is causing serious unease even within the DfE, we understand.</p> <p>Providers are expected to be told the number of places they will have funding for. It is thought university-led provision will be scaled back and there will be a big rise in places routed through School Direct, the school-based training introduced by Michael Gove.</p> <p>Sources close to the DfE say there was a battle between Gove and his appointee Charlie Taylor, head of the National College for Teaching and Leadership, on one hand, and the Liberal Democrat schools minister, David Laws, on the other, with Laws wanting to avoid destabilising university-led provision. Despite Gove’s exit, Taylor seems to have won.</p> <p>Our source says: “There’s no debate in the DfE as to whether this is the rational thing to do. It’s simply ideological vandalism. No other country is doing this.”</p> <p>A DfE spokeswoman says: “The School Direct programme is in response to what schools want. Universities will continue to play an important role.”</p> <h2>‘British values’ take over school websites</h2> <p>You click on a <a href=\"http://nicolmereschool.co.uk/index.php/curriculum/british-values/\">school website</a>, sit back – or should you stand? – and the national anthem plays. It’s “British values” in action on school websites.</p> <p>One school, Rush Green primary in Romford, Essex, interestingly<a href=\"http://www.rushgreenprimary.org.uk/smsc/british-values-statement\"> includes discussion of local heroes Bobby Moore and Dame Vera Lynn in its coverage of the topic</a>. Bill Bolloten, an independent consultant, who pointed us to three such sites, says some heads responded very quickly after Gove’s statement in response to the Trojan Horse affair in June when <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/birmingham-schools-secretary-of-state-for-educations-statement\">he said he would put the “promotion of British values” at the heart of every school</a>.</p> <p>Bolloten tells us: “Schools do need to think about how they develop pupils’ social, moral, spiritual and cultural development. I worry that they are being blown off course by over-emphasising ‘British values’ – which are contested – because of political pressure.”</p> <p>No one from the school using the national anthem, Nicol Mere in Wigan, was available for comment about the webpage, which we understand was placed on the site this term.</p> <h2>More delays at Durand’s boarding school</h2> <p>A multi-million pound boarding academy in the South Downs has still not opened, weeks after term began for the south London children who will be educated there. Questions are being asked afresh about the Durand Boarding Academy, which was enthusiastically backed by Gove. Last month, when we learned it had not opened on-site in Stedham, West Sussex, we were told that this had always been planned and that pupils would be there later in the month.</p> <p>As of last week, they had still not arrived, with whispers that a half-term date was more likely. Why the delay?</p> <p>A spokesman says: “It has always been Durand’s intention for children to spend the first few weeks of term at our Stockwell [south London] site, before moving down to West Sussex.” And yet in an email on 5 September, the same spokesman had said the move would be “by the end of the month”. Now, though, there are still “a few final touches” to make.</p> <p>Meanwhile, one local encountered a bus carrying adults – possibly staff and parents – lost en route to the site last week. Sam St Clair-Ford says he had to give the driver directions, as the bus was heading the wrong way up a narrow lane through which it could not pass. We hope this is not a metaphor for the whole project.</p> <h2>The high price of forced academisation</h2> <p>When an interim board is parachuted into a school to turn it forcibly into an academy, how much do they earn?</p> <p>One consultant was paid nearly £20,000 over eight months, a Freedom of Information request has revealed. The unnamed member of the three-person interim executive board at Cavell primary in Norwich was paid £18,247.50, the local authority disclosed to a campaigner. Normally, school governors are not paid at all.</p> <p>Parent Rachel Ward, who campaigned against the academisation, said it was a “staggering waste of money”. Norfolk should have saved its cash by supporting the school’s existing governing body, she says. A spokesman for Norfolk council says the costs at this school “were higher than normal due to the complex nature of the school’s academisation process” and a judicial review. Also, the people needed “a particular skill set to oversee improvement”.</p> <h2>And the record for the smallest free school …</h2> <p>Finally, some free schools seem to be vying to have the smallest number of pupils. Last month we learned that Trinity academy, a secondary in Lambeth, south London, <a href=\"http://www.academiesweek.co.uk/secondary-opens-with-17-pupils/ \">opened with 17 on its books</a>. Meanwhile, not so far away in Morden, Park community school, a primary run by the Chapel St charity, which has links to the Salvation Army, emerged into the <a href=\"http://www.wimbledonguardian.co.uk/news/11506905.Controversial_charity_wins_right_to_open_secondary_school_in_Merton/?ref=rss&amp;utm_medium=facebook&amp;utm_source=twitterfeed\">world with only 12 children, housed in a former Salvation Army hut</a>.</p> <p>But perhaps leading the pack so far is the Leeds Jewish free school, a secondary school which, <a href=\"http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/education/the-3m-leeds-school-with-just-21-pupils-1-6864311\">the Yorkshire Post reports</a>, has just 21 students despite now being in its second year. Value-for-money questions about the free schools project are unlikely to go away.</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"39","wordcount":"920","commentCloseDate":"2014-10-17T06:00:18Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2014-10-10T16:03:10Z","firstPublicationDate":"2014-10-14T06:00:18Z","internalComposerCode":"5438033ee4b08c06d131fae1","internalOctopusCode":"9627405","internalPageCode":"2173812","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-07-19T14:30:13Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-10-14T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/42bzf","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","lang":"en","internalRevision":"44","internalShortId":"/p/42bzf"},"tags":[{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/education","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"education","sectionName":"Education","webTitle":"Education","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsec